<br>
If the GM said it didn't work anymore, he/she most likely meant: <br>
<br>
A. You can't invis yourself, as Nanur mentioned, or<br>
<br>
B. You can't &lt;(open)&gt; a trade window while invisible.  <br>
<br>
Note that OPEN is the operative phrase here.  When you open a trade window while invis, invis drops.  However, you can still do pretty much whatever you want while it's already open.  Spells still affect you, and people can still cast on you.  Trick works, but GMs would rather the player base didn't spread it around.  Since we have to learn this trick for our epic quest, I feel no compunctions against using or sharing this trick, there really isn't another good or easy way around this without having to redo parts of it.  I shouldn't have to redo an entire quest because some programer got a wild hair up his butt when he decided to ensure some players couldn't sell epic MQs to others, and thereby screwed it up for all of us.<br>
<br>
GMs are only going to be so helpful to you.  They've gotta balance solving your problems with making sure they don't give anything out that might allow you to exploit errors in the software.  Unfortunately for us, 'errors in the software' are situationally defined by each individual GM.  To some of them, an Iksar who worked at maxing his Gfay factions is a serious error who should be corrected, to others an AE group is a serious exploit.  Unless Sony starts giving them standardized classes on what is and is not considered an exploit or unfair use of the game, we're not gonna see any sort of consistency with tech support.<br>
